\subsection{\href{https://beta.lmfdb.org/knowledge/show/group.size_conjugacy_class}{Size of a conjugacy class.}}
\begin{definition*}\label{group.size_conjugacy_class}
\uses{group.center,group.conjugacy_class,group.order}
The \textbf{size} of a \hyperref[group.conjugacy_class]{conjugacy class} of a finite group is the cardinality of the set of elements conjugate to each other.  

By the Orbit-Stabilizer Theorem, the size of a conjugacy class divides the \hyperref[group.order]{order} of the group. Since conjugacy classes partition a group, the sum of the sizes of the conjugacy classes equals the size of the group.

A conjugacy class is of size $1$ if and only if the element is in the \hyperref[group.center]{center} of the group.


\end{definition*}


